00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.170
about why it's important
to understand introversion

00:05:35.170 --> 00:05:38.080
and what it is, and give
people opportunities

00:05:38.080 --> 00:05:41.400
who aren't necessarily the first
one to speak at the meeting,

00:05:41.400 --> 00:05:43.710
for instance, or
the one who doesn't

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:46.390
like to be put on the spot,
to come up with answers.

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:47.960
And a big part of
what we learned

00:05:47.960 --> 00:05:50.905
through this scientific
investigation of creativity

00:05:50.905 --> 00:05:52.280
is that a lot of
great creativity

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:55.219
comes through solitude,
comes through daydreaming.

00:05:55.219 --> 00:05:56.760
It comes through
things that we don't

00:05:56.760 --> 00:06:00.562
promote in our school system,
and often in the workplace.

00:06:00.562 --> 00:06:01.520
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:04.530
Like Scott was saying,
introversion and exploration

00:06:04.530 --> 00:06:06.540
was a central
contradiction that we

00:06:06.540 --> 00:06:10.015
explored within a
series of paradoxes

00:06:10.015 --> 00:06:11.731
seen in highly creative people.

00:06:11.731 --> 00:06:13.230
There was a really
interesting study

00:06:13.230 --> 00:06:16.000
done on heavy metal
musicians which

00:06:16.000 --> 00:06:19.800
found that they actually are
very sensitive and introverted,

00:06:19.800 --> 00:06:23.790
and say things backstage
like they need lots of time

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:26.840
by themselves and they enjoy
daydreaming and engaging

00:06:26.840 --> 00:06:30.960
in a world of fantasy, and
that they are easily disrupted

00:06:30.960 --> 00:06:33.870
by loud noises-- which is a
very strange thing to hear

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:35.750
from a heavy metal musician.

00:06:35.750 --> 00:06:39.520
But again and again in the
lives of different types

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:42.780
of creative people, we see
these very startling contrasts.

00:06:42.780 --> 00:06:46.150
So these heavy metal musicians
were very bold and brash

00:06:46.150 --> 00:06:49.214
onstage, and that was
very much something

00:06:49.214 --> 00:06:50.630
a part of themselves
and something

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:52.080
that they enjoyed doing.

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:55.450
So they did have extroversion
in that sense, and charisma.

00:06:55.450 --> 00:06:59.910
But they were also very shy,
very often isolated, sensitive,

00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:01.140
introverted.

00:07:01.140 --> 00:07:04.380
And so these contradictions are
pretty much across the board

00:07:04.380 --> 00:07:08.407
present in people who
have eminent creative work

00:07:08.407 --> 00:07:09.240
that they have done.

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:11.900
And this is partly
because-- well, it's

00:07:11.900 --> 00:07:15.460
possible that these sort
of inner tensions that we

00:07:15.460 --> 00:07:19.070
feel within ourselves give
rise to the desire to create.

00:07:19.070 --> 00:07:22.240
And it's actually been found
that creative writers score

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:24.940
both in the top 10% of
the general population

00:07:24.940 --> 00:07:27.430
on tests of mental
illness, and also

00:07:27.430 --> 00:07:30.290
in the top 15% on
tests of mental health.

00:07:30.290 --> 00:07:32.400
So how is that possible?

00:07:32.400 --> 00:07:35.380
It may be that people who
are driven to create just

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:39.097
are more open to this
broad sense of themselves,

00:07:39.097 --> 00:07:41.180
are more intimate with
both the dark and the light

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:41.990
within themselves.

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:44.250
And that may be
sort of a catalyst

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:46.460
for creative exploration,
for creativity

00:07:46.460 --> 00:07:48.802
as a way of trying to
understand themselves.

00:07:48.802 --> 00:07:49.220
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Yeah.

00:07:49.220 --> 00:07:50.910
We're starting to see
this a bit in the brain.

00:07:50.910 --> 00:07:51.760
We're doing neuroscience.

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:53.259
Do we have anyone
in this room who's

00:07:53.259 --> 00:07:54.910
interested in
neuroscience at all?

00:07:54.910 --> 00:07:56.430
Oh, excellent.

00:07:56.430 --> 00:07:58.200
So we found that
three major brain

00:07:58.200 --> 00:08:01.290
networks are important
for the creative process.

00:08:01.290 --> 00:08:04.550
Traditionally, what's called
the executive attention network

00:08:04.550 --> 00:08:07.052
has been considered
the most important one.

00:08:07.052 --> 00:08:08.510
And the executive
attention network

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:12.280
involves your ability to
focus on the outside world,

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:15.120
to hold lots of different bits
of information in your head

00:08:15.120 --> 00:08:16.490
at once and integrate them.

00:08:16.490 --> 00:08:20.009
When you're programming, when
you're really focusing-- let's

00:08:20.009 --> 00:08:22.050
say you're going through
like 5,000 lines of code

00:08:22.050 --> 00:08:23.091
to find that one mistake.

00:08:23.091 --> 00:08:26.250
The executive attention
network is extremely important.

00:08:26.250 --> 00:08:28.087
But a very under-rated
brain network

00:08:28.087 --> 00:08:29.670
that's been discovered
in recent years

00:08:29.670 --> 00:08:31.870
is called the default
mode brain network.

00:08:31.870 --> 00:08:35.210
It was discovered accidentally
by a cognitive neuroscience,

00:08:35.210 --> 00:08:37.650
because cognitive
neuroscientists weren't

00:08:37.650 --> 00:08:40.970
interested in what was
going on in your own head

00:08:40.970 --> 00:08:44.380
while you were being part of a
experiment that wasn't related

00:08:44.380 --> 00:08:45.640
to the actual experiment.

00:08:45.640 --> 00:08:47.534
So if the experimenter
is like, is this line

00:08:47.534 --> 00:08:48.450
bigger than this line?

00:08:48.450 --> 00:08:53.620
Or comprehend this boring
reading comprehension passage--

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:55.740
any of your daydreaming,
any of your fantasies,

00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:57.190
your future
thoughts, strivings--

00:08:57.190 --> 00:09:00.130
all that was considered
noise in the laboratory.

00:09:00.130 --> 00:09:03.820
Until recently, some really--
am I allowed to say "badass?"

00:09:03.820 --> 00:09:06.290
Badass neuroscientists
were like,

00:09:06.290 --> 00:09:08.840
we wonder if there's any
value at all to what's

00:09:08.840 --> 00:09:11.260
going on by default
in their head.

00:09:11.260 --> 00:09:12.830
What is that cognition
when we're not

00:09:12.830 --> 00:09:14.130
telling them what to do?

00:09:14.130 --> 00:09:16.410
And it opened up this
whole new line of research

00:09:16.410 --> 00:09:19.270
in cognitive neuroscience, this
discovery of the default mode

00:09:19.270 --> 00:09:20.044
network.

00:09:20.044 --> 00:09:21.710
We like to call it
the imagination brain

00:09:21.710 --> 00:09:24.485
network, because it turns
out this network is not

00:09:24.485 --> 00:09:27.290
just associated with
daydreaming and mind-wandering

00:09:27.290 --> 00:09:29.370
and imagination, but
it's also associated

00:09:29.370 --> 00:09:31.680
with making meaning out
of your experiences.

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:34.040
When you disrupt
this brain network,

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:37.450
you find that you also see
disruptions in sense of self

00:09:37.450 --> 00:09:41.520
and your capacity to create
a narrative about your life

00:09:41.520 --> 00:09:42.930
and make meaning.

00:09:42.930 --> 00:09:44.719
Of course-- maybe
it's not of course,

00:09:44.719 --> 00:09:46.760
but did you know that the
self is a construction?

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:48.880
It's not actually a
thing, a real thing

00:09:48.880 --> 00:09:50.540
we discovered physically?

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:52.400
Oh, there's the self.

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:55.860
This is a very age-old question.

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:58.970
But what we do know
is our self-concept.

00:09:58.970 --> 00:10:01.611
And it's constantly
being revised.

00:10:01.611 --> 00:10:03.110
Our self-concept
is constantly being

00:10:03.110 --> 00:10:05.400
revised by other
people's opinions of us

00:10:05.400 --> 00:10:07.192
and by our own opinions
of ourselves, which

00:10:07.192 --> 00:10:07.941
is very important.

00:10:07.941 --> 00:10:10.250
It influences how we engage
with others in the world.

00:10:10.250 --> 00:10:11.850
And you find this
imagination is very

00:10:11.850 --> 00:10:14.647
important for that
natural process.

00:10:14.647 --> 00:10:16.730
So we find those two brain
networks are important.

00:10:16.730 --> 00:10:18.100
And there's a
third brain network

00:10:18.100 --> 00:10:19.141
that is very under-rated.

00:10:19.141 --> 00:10:20.880
It's called the
salience brain network.

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:23.460
And that's associated with your
ability-- not your ability,

00:10:23.460 --> 00:10:24.267
but motivation.

00:10:24.267 --> 00:10:25.850
How much do things
in your environment

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:27.240
capture your attention?

00:10:27.240 --> 00:10:31.370
His salience network wasn't
activated in this talk-- maybe.

00:10:31.370 --> 00:10:33.014
I don't know.

00:10:33.014 --> 00:10:34.430
But the salience
network is really

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:36.060
important for
helping to tag things

00:10:36.060 --> 00:10:38.025
as relevant or irrelevant.

00:10:38.025 --> 00:10:39.650
So if you're in a
really boring lecture

00:10:39.650 --> 00:10:43.900
or you're in a boring--
most of us in school

00:10:43.900 --> 00:10:46.060
were forced to pay
attention to a teacher.

00:10:46.060 --> 00:10:48.577
And that salience network
has passed the baton over

00:10:48.577 --> 00:10:50.160
to the imagination
network, and that's

00:10:50.160 --> 00:10:52.560
when we start daydreaming
and mind-wandering.

00:10:52.560 --> 00:10:54.060
But when that
salience network says,

00:10:54.060 --> 00:10:56.430
wow, that's really
interesting-- then

00:10:56.430 --> 00:10:59.190
it passes the baton over to the
executive attention network,

00:10:59.190 --> 00:11:00.920
and that's when we
really can focus.

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:03.870
So in a lot of ways, the
key to everything in life

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:06.070
is activating that
salience network, which

00:11:06.070 --> 00:11:07.980
is at a subconscious level.

00:11:07.980 --> 00:11:10.100
And it also is influenced
by our learning process

00:11:10.100 --> 00:11:11.142
and our past experiences.

00:11:11.142 --> 00:11:12.100
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:11:12.100 --> 00:11:14.080
And so where that comes
in with the personality

00:11:14.080 --> 00:11:16.500
contradictions is
that in most people,

00:11:16.500 --> 00:11:20.550
the external attention network
and the internal default

00:11:20.550 --> 00:11:22.271
network are at odds.

00:11:22.271 --> 00:11:24.270
We're either using one
or we're using the other,

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:26.950
depending on the situation
and the task at hand.

00:11:26.950 --> 00:11:29.270
But in creative people,
something really interesting

00:11:29.270 --> 00:11:32.860
is happening-- or when people
are engaged in creative work

00:11:32.860 --> 00:11:35.750
and develop these
creative skills,

00:11:35.750 --> 00:11:37.800
these brain arcs
actually harmonize,

00:11:37.800 --> 00:11:41.300
and there's a rapid sort of
switching between the networks

00:11:41.300 --> 00:11:42.880
and people become
very well equipped

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:44.370
at using them together.

00:11:44.370 --> 00:11:45.970
So it's kind of
like these opposites

00:11:45.970 --> 00:11:49.370
coming together, even on
the level of neurology.

00:11:49.370 --> 00:11:52.150
So we see in the level of
the brain and the personality

00:11:52.150 --> 00:11:55.420
and the creative process, which
also tends to be kind of back

00:11:55.420 --> 00:11:58.570
and forth and is not a linear
progression for most people--

00:11:58.570 --> 00:12:02.370
I'm sure many of us can relate
to procrastinating and doing

00:12:02.370 --> 00:12:05.320
nothing on a project, and then
suddenly it all comes at once.

00:12:05.320 --> 00:12:07.300
Or maybe not you guys.

00:12:07.300 --> 00:12:09.527
You made it to Google, so--

00:12:09.527 --> 00:12:11.860
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Google
can't be shut down for a day

00:12:11.860 --> 00:12:13.193
because you guys procrastinated.

00:12:13.193 --> 00:12:14.617
We need you.

00:12:14.617 --> 00:12:16.700
You've got how many people
million people every 20

00:12:16.700 --> 00:12:17.199
seconds?

00:12:17.199 --> 00:12:19.270
What does it say up there.

