CAROLYN GREGOIRE:
But even Picasso

00:12:21.140 --> 00:12:25.100
late in his career, when he had
made thousands of paintings,

00:12:25.100 --> 00:12:28.460
his process still didn't
look to be what you would

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:30.072
expect from a seasoned painter.

00:12:30.072 --> 00:12:31.530
He would kind of
go back and forth,

00:12:31.530 --> 00:12:36.017
and he would create sketches
that sometimes would have

00:12:36.017 --> 00:12:37.600
a sort of linear
progression, and then

00:12:37.600 --> 00:12:39.614
he would go back
to the earliest one

00:12:39.614 --> 00:12:41.030
and then put that
in the painting.

00:12:41.030 --> 00:12:42.738
And it would seem to
be this process more

00:12:42.738 --> 00:12:45.030
of blind experimentation
than any sort

00:12:45.030 --> 00:12:47.939
of logical, orderly
sort of process.

00:12:47.939 --> 00:12:49.480
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
Let me tell them

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:51.950
about a study that came out
after our book was published

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:53.600
that is really interesting.

00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:56.725
We're kind of having a new
understanding of personality

00:12:56.725 --> 00:12:57.600
and the way it works.

00:12:57.600 --> 00:12:59.600
Raise your hand if you
think the way personality

00:12:59.600 --> 00:13:02.430
works is it's something that you
have these stable dispositions

00:13:02.430 --> 00:13:04.870
that don't really change that
much throughout your life?

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:07.842
Raise your hand if you
think that's-- OK, good.

00:13:07.842 --> 00:13:09.050
Good.

00:13:09.050 --> 00:13:12.250
So it turns out that, through
the course of our day--

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:14.430
I feel I can get really
technical with this audience

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:16.263
and you guys will really
get me, so I'm just

00:13:16.263 --> 00:13:17.220
going to be technical.

00:13:17.220 --> 00:13:19.190
So the way we think
of personality now

00:13:19.190 --> 00:13:21.000
is density distributions.

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.260
So each one of us has
a density distribution

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:25.029
for a whole wide
range of traits.

00:13:25.029 --> 00:13:27.570
But what that means is that it's
kind of like you have a bell

00:13:27.570 --> 00:13:30.400
curve throughout
the day of-- no one

00:13:30.400 --> 00:13:32.340
is purely extroverted
or purely introverted.

00:13:32.340 --> 00:13:34.048
And what you see is
that within a person,

00:13:34.048 --> 00:13:36.870
you actually cycle through
every introverted-extroverted

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:37.904
behavior.

00:13:37.904 --> 00:13:39.070
At the core we're all human.

00:13:39.070 --> 00:13:41.446
So you know how you have people
who say, I'm an introvert

00:13:41.446 --> 00:13:44.028
and they're so proud of it, and
they're like, that's who I am.

00:13:44.028 --> 00:13:45.100
I'm never an extrovert.

00:13:45.100 --> 00:13:46.970
But if you actually follow
them throughout the day,

00:13:46.970 --> 00:13:49.260
like scientifically you
follow them throughout the day

00:13:49.260 --> 00:13:51.040
and you have them
report their thinking--

00:13:51.040 --> 00:13:52.840
you find they actually
extrovert a lot more

00:13:52.840 --> 00:13:54.870
than they're willing to admit.

00:13:54.870 --> 00:13:57.395
What you do see, though, is
that their density distribution

00:13:57.395 --> 00:14:01.394
is skewed much more towards the
interviewed side on average--

00:14:01.394 --> 00:14:02.810
not even on average,
just in terms

00:14:02.810 --> 00:14:05.060
of the skew of a distribution.

00:14:05.060 --> 00:14:06.670
And we're starting
to extend that now

00:14:06.670 --> 00:14:10.190
to things that have normally
been non-clinical traits,

00:14:10.190 --> 00:14:13.474
like narcissism for instance--
things like schizophrenia.

00:14:13.474 --> 00:14:15.890
It actually turns out that
these things were breaking down

00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:17.880
the boundaries of what
these things mean between,

00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:19.630
oh, there's the clinical
people that we put them

00:14:19.630 --> 00:14:21.296
in the mental institution
who have that,

00:14:21.296 --> 00:14:24.220
and then there are the rest
of us who are not in clinical.

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:24.980
We're good.

00:14:24.980 --> 00:14:27.740
But we're not good,
you Know Or they're

00:14:27.740 --> 00:14:32.170
not bad, is how I prefer
a positive spin on it.

00:14:32.170 --> 00:14:35.060
And so how this relates is that
when you look at the brain,

00:14:35.060 --> 00:14:39.060
you find that actually
there's a lot of similarities

00:14:39.060 --> 00:14:41.800
between schizophrenic patients
and creative people when

00:14:41.800 --> 00:14:43.405
you ask them to
solve creative tasks.

00:14:43.405 --> 00:14:44.780
That's where I'm
going with this.

00:14:44.780 --> 00:14:46.130
I wanted to tie it all together.

00:14:46.130 --> 00:14:48.130
You actually find there's
a lot of similarities.

00:14:48.130 --> 00:14:49.620
Where the differences
are is when

00:14:49.620 --> 00:14:51.620
you follow them throughout
the course of the day

00:14:51.620 --> 00:14:54.120
and you find that actually,
creative people are

00:14:54.120 --> 00:14:56.490
more able to return to reality.

00:14:56.490 --> 00:15:01.090
So they're equally as capable
of jumping out and taking a risk

00:15:01.090 --> 00:15:02.680
and thinking really
imaginatively

00:15:02.680 --> 00:15:04.931
and quote psychotically.

00:15:04.931 --> 00:15:06.930
But what they're able to
do throughout their day

00:15:06.930 --> 00:15:09.150
is their density
distribution of schizophrenia

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:13.630
is much less skewed to
the one and the other

00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:14.842
for schizophrenic patients.

00:15:14.842 --> 00:15:17.300
And that's a new emerging way
of thinking about personality

00:15:17.300 --> 00:15:19.230
that I think is going to
have profound implications

00:15:19.230 --> 00:15:20.090
in the coming years.

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:21.660
Does that make sense?

00:15:21.660 --> 00:15:22.618
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:15:22.618 --> 00:15:25.270
And going back to this finding
that creative writers were

00:15:25.270 --> 00:15:28.640
sort of both more mentally
ill and more mentally healthy

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:34.640
than other people, I think part
of the mentally ill aspect--

00:15:34.640 --> 00:15:37.610
part of the aspect that is
related to mental illness

00:15:37.610 --> 00:15:39.840
is so something
called schizotypy

00:15:39.840 --> 00:15:43.020
is a spectrum ranging
on one end, which

00:15:43.020 --> 00:15:45.490
is sort of imaginativeness
and on the other, full-blown

00:15:45.490 --> 00:15:46.600
schizophrenia.

00:15:46.600 --> 00:15:49.200
And so what's been
found is highly

00:15:49.200 --> 00:15:50.840
creative people
may have just some

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:54.740
of the more positive traits
associated with schizophrenia,

00:15:54.740 --> 00:15:56.500
without the more harmful ones.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:15:58.650
So that would be things
like magical thinking

00:15:58.650 --> 00:16:04.070
and a tendency to see patterns
and to find order and disorder,

00:16:04.070 --> 00:16:08.030
and very unusual perceptions
or heightened perceptions.

00:16:08.030 --> 00:16:11.190
So maybe if they're
listening to chimes,

00:16:11.190 --> 00:16:13.090
they would hear more
sound in the chimes

00:16:13.090 --> 00:16:15.160
than the average person would.

00:16:15.160 --> 00:16:17.950
And so these are things
that our society associates

00:16:17.950 --> 00:16:20.100
with mental illness,
but I've been thinking

00:16:20.100 --> 00:16:21.720
of this list of traits.

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:24.600
Do they really seem so
negative, and can that actually

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:26.640
maybe lead us to
reconsider mental illness

00:16:26.640 --> 00:16:31.950
and how we treat mental
disorders in our culture?

00:16:31.950 --> 00:16:33.770
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Absolutely.

