00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:53.390
restricted to a select group of
artists, scientists, writers,

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:55.200
or musicians.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:58.250
Why do you suggest that
personal creativity

00:16:58.250 --> 00:17:01.530
is important for
everyone's sense of being?

00:17:01.530 --> 00:17:03.270
It's important for
everyone's sense

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:06.967
of well-being, not just a few
selected creative artists.

00:17:06.967 --> 00:17:08.050
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Yeah.

00:17:08.050 --> 00:17:09.612
We talk about well-being
in the book a little bit,

00:17:09.612 --> 00:17:10.903
so that's an exciting question.

00:17:10.903 --> 00:17:11.987
Do you want to cover that?

00:17:11.987 --> 00:17:12.944
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:17:12.944 --> 00:17:15.540
I think creativity is just
kind of a natural part of who

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:16.339
we are.

00:17:16.339 --> 00:17:19.260
And we see this in the
case of children at play.

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:22.200
Play is not a thing that some
children do and some children

00:17:22.200 --> 00:17:22.700
don't.

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:25.420
It's actually a natural and
healthy and very important

00:17:25.420 --> 00:17:27.470
part of child development.

00:17:27.470 --> 00:17:30.590
And when there is not
play, there's a problem.

00:17:30.590 --> 00:17:34.110
And so from that and
from other research,

00:17:34.110 --> 00:17:36.310
we can kind of deduce
that creativity is just

00:17:36.310 --> 00:17:38.610
a fundamental human
characteristic.

00:17:38.610 --> 00:17:42.500
And so it doesn't always
take the form of a Picasso

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:47.260
or a genius musician, but
creativity is just-- I mean,

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:50.452
we define it as-- well, I
guess science defines it as--

00:17:50.452 --> 00:17:51.600
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: We should
have defined creativity first.

00:17:51.600 --> 00:17:53.100
CAROLYN GREGOIRE:
Science defines it

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:55.380
as novelty and usefulness.

00:17:55.380 --> 00:17:58.180
So we kind of define
it broadly as just

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:00.340
bringing something
new into the world,

00:18:00.340 --> 00:18:02.220
whether that's a new
idea or just a new way

00:18:02.220 --> 00:18:08.047
of seeing a problem, or a new
way of presenting something.

00:18:08.047 --> 00:18:09.630
There are so many
forms creativity can

00:18:09.630 --> 00:18:12.190
and so many everyday forms
that it does take-- from what

00:18:12.190 --> 00:18:14.050
we choose to wear and
put something together

00:18:14.050 --> 00:18:18.767
in a different way to the
way that we phrase just even

00:18:18.767 --> 00:18:20.600
a sentence in an email
that has a little bit

00:18:20.600 --> 00:18:23.177
more personal meaning.

00:18:23.177 --> 00:18:25.260
I think everyone is creative,
and you can't really

00:18:25.260 --> 00:18:27.520
escape creativity when you
look at it in that sense.

00:18:27.520 --> 00:18:30.200
And so the more
we do exercise it

00:18:30.200 --> 00:18:33.600
and the more we do bring
new things into the world

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:36.180
and bring some sort
of self-expression

00:18:36.180 --> 00:18:39.830
into what we do, generally,
the more joy that we'll

00:18:39.830 --> 00:18:40.960
have in our lives.

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:41.170
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Yeah.

00:18:41.170 --> 00:18:42.380
There's definitely
research showing

00:18:42.380 --> 00:18:43.930
that everyday
forms of creativity

00:18:43.930 --> 00:18:46.280
is correlated with
feeling vitality

00:18:46.280 --> 00:18:49.760
in life, optimism, a sense
of meaning in your life.

00:18:49.760 --> 00:18:51.230
So it's very true.

00:18:51.230 --> 00:18:53.570
And at the highest levels,
at the genius level,

00:18:53.570 --> 00:18:56.910
it is a myth that mental illness
is required for creativity.

00:18:56.910 --> 00:18:58.520
I want to be very
clear about that.

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:00.530
But when you find
is an association,

00:19:00.530 --> 00:19:04.050
because a lot of people who
have had very harsh childhood

00:19:04.050 --> 00:19:06.229
experiences are
actually overrepresented

00:19:06.229 --> 00:19:07.020
in creative fields.

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:08.920
People who've had some
hardships in their childhood

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:11.110
is actually over-represented
in the history books.

00:19:11.110 --> 00:19:12.890
And a lot of psychologists
are trying to figure out why.

00:19:12.890 --> 00:19:14.100
What's going on there?

00:19:14.100 --> 00:19:16.140
Is it that you need
to have hardships

00:19:16.140 --> 00:19:17.150
in order to be creative?

00:19:17.150 --> 00:19:19.290
And it turns out
that these hardships

00:19:19.290 --> 00:19:22.650
create a sense of
otherness in them that

00:19:22.650 --> 00:19:24.630
allows them to see a
world in a different way,

00:19:24.630 --> 00:19:26.200
allows them to step back.

00:19:26.200 --> 00:19:28.759
And also, it gives them more
confidence to take risks,

00:19:28.759 --> 00:19:30.800
because they're like, oh,
what do I have to lose?

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:33.700
I've already lost
it all pretty much.

00:19:33.700 --> 00:19:35.636
So they're much more
willing to take risks.

00:19:35.636 --> 00:19:38.260
And also, another thing is that
a lot of creative people who've

00:19:38.260 --> 00:19:40.600
had hardships, there's
an emerging field

00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:43.100
called post-traumatic growth
that we talk about in the book.

00:19:43.100 --> 00:19:47.930
So a lot of them use their
hardships to grow creatively.

00:19:47.930 --> 00:19:52.329
So a lot of creative writers
will put it into their work.

00:19:52.329 --> 00:19:53.870
They'll write about
it in their work.

00:19:53.870 --> 00:19:55.536
I'm trying to think
right now in my head

00:19:55.536 --> 00:19:58.610
