00:21:42.340 --> 00:21:44.660
But it's very critical
to creative thinking.

00:21:44.660 --> 00:21:48.090
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: I did an
international study on showers,

00:21:48.090 --> 00:21:50.810
and more people reported
creative insights in the shower

00:21:50.810 --> 00:21:52.515
than they did at work.

00:21:52.515 --> 00:21:53.890
CAROLYN GREGOIRE:
So day-dreaming

00:21:53.890 --> 00:21:57.590
is pretty critical to the
creative thinking processes.

00:21:57.590 --> 00:21:59.940
But mindfulness is as well.

00:21:59.940 --> 00:22:03.720
It's easy to see how we need
to be able to focus and to pay

00:22:03.720 --> 00:22:07.680
attention, and to really sustain
our attention on whatever we're

00:22:07.680 --> 00:22:10.700
doing in order to
actually do creative work.

00:22:10.700 --> 00:22:13.320
So we kind of need daydreaming
for this idea generation,

00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:15.240
and then mindfulness
for actually making

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:17.340
our ideas become a reality.

00:22:17.340 --> 00:22:22.390
And so these kind of thinking
processes can be at odds,

00:22:22.390 --> 00:22:25.350
but creative people do tend
to find a kind of synthesis

00:22:25.350 --> 00:22:26.560
between them.

00:22:26.560 --> 00:22:30.170
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: With that
said, we debate often a lot

00:22:30.170 --> 00:22:33.140
whether expert mindful
people, are they creative?

00:22:33.140 --> 00:22:35.030
And that's still a
question open for debate.

00:22:35.030 --> 00:22:38.070
But the research is kind
of mixed in that, showing

00:22:38.070 --> 00:22:41.190
that too much mindfulness on
the outside world or too much

00:22:41.190 --> 00:22:44.105
focus does limit your career
potential in a lot of ways

00:22:44.105 --> 00:22:45.480
if you don't have
the flexibility

00:22:45.480 --> 00:22:48.870
to go back and daydream as
well about what you've learned.

00:22:48.870 --> 00:22:50.110
So that's what we're seeing.

00:22:50.110 --> 00:22:50.550
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:22:50.550 --> 00:22:52.258
And actually, certain
types of meditation

00:22:52.258 --> 00:22:55.410
are better than others when
it comes to stimulating

00:22:55.410 --> 00:22:56.270
creative thinking.

00:22:56.270 --> 00:22:59.811
Does anyone practice TM,
transcendental meditation?

00:22:59.811 --> 00:23:00.310
No?

00:23:00.310 --> 00:23:01.380
I'm surprised.

00:23:01.380 --> 00:23:06.264
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Does anyone
do meditation in any form?

00:23:06.264 --> 00:23:07.930
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: So
forms of meditation

00:23:07.930 --> 00:23:12.190
that sort of encourage awareness
of the internal thought

00:23:12.190 --> 00:23:15.120
processes-- we can be mindful
to actually our own thoughts

00:23:15.120 --> 00:23:16.550
and our own imagination.

00:23:16.550 --> 00:23:18.670
We usually think of
mindfulness as being

00:23:18.670 --> 00:23:22.630
mindful to the external world,
to the present moment in terms

00:23:22.630 --> 00:23:23.880
of our immediate surroundings.

00:23:23.880 --> 00:23:27.340
But sometimes meditation,
like transcendental meditation

00:23:27.340 --> 00:23:30.550
and open monitoring
meditation, encourage

00:23:30.550 --> 00:23:32.710
becoming more mindful
of everything that's

00:23:32.710 --> 00:23:35.010
in our internal landscape.

00:23:35.010 --> 00:23:37.610
So there is an ability
to allow the mind

00:23:37.610 --> 00:23:39.190
to wander, to pay
attention to that,

00:23:39.190 --> 00:23:40.960
and then to bring it back.

00:23:40.960 --> 00:23:43.040
And these types of
meditations, more so

00:23:43.040 --> 00:23:45.960
than a very strict,
intense zen meditation

00:23:45.960 --> 00:23:48.710
where you're focusing
just very intensely

00:23:48.710 --> 00:23:52.490
on some external
object-- these tend

00:23:52.490 --> 00:23:54.214
to be more effective
for creativity,

00:23:54.214 --> 00:23:56.380
because they're bringing
together those two thinking

00:23:56.380 --> 00:23:58.430
processes.

00:23:58.430 --> 00:23:59.630
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

00:23:59.630 --> 00:24:02.210
I would also like to
open the floor for anyone

00:24:02.210 --> 00:24:03.830
if you have any Q&amp;A questions.

00:24:03.830 --> 00:24:06.324
If not, then OK.

00:24:06.324 --> 00:24:06.824
Sure.

00:24:09.818 --> 00:24:13.740
AUDIENCE: I'm wondering,
from this knowledge, what

00:24:13.740 --> 00:24:17.127
is the actionable
thing that we can do?

00:24:17.127 --> 00:24:18.960
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
That's a fair question.

00:24:18.960 --> 00:24:19.940
Fair question.

00:24:19.940 --> 00:24:22.580
Scientists cringe a little bit
when they get that question,

00:24:22.580 --> 00:24:24.371
because they're like,
that's not what I do.

00:24:24.371 --> 00:24:26.440
It's not what I do.

00:24:26.440 --> 00:24:28.500
But people want to know.

00:24:28.500 --> 00:24:31.455
And we talk about some
actionable things in this book.

00:24:31.455 --> 00:24:32.830
And I think the
best way to think

00:24:32.830 --> 00:24:36.090
about it is that creativity is
a way of being in the world.

00:24:36.090 --> 00:24:38.340
Don't think of creativity
as only this thing

00:24:38.340 --> 00:24:39.780
that geniuses do.

00:24:39.780 --> 00:24:41.610
It's a way of relating
to your world.

00:24:41.610 --> 00:24:43.818
And we really feel, to the
extent to which you follow

00:24:43.818 --> 00:24:46.175
these 10 things
in this book, you

00:24:46.175 --> 00:24:48.355
are in effect living
a creative lifestyle.

00:24:48.355 --> 00:24:49.730
And you're increasing
the chances

00:24:49.730 --> 00:24:51.190
there'll be creative insights.

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:52.590
It's very important
to build time

00:24:52.590 --> 00:24:55.800
into your day to have solitude.

00:24:55.800 --> 00:24:58.410
Too many meetings is going
to stifle creativity,

00:24:58.410 --> 00:25:02.600
if there are any project
managers listening to that.

00:25:02.600 --> 00:25:06.080
It's really important to
constantly push yourself out

00:25:06.080 --> 00:25:07.210
of your comfort zone.

00:25:07.210 --> 00:25:10.150
We have a whole chapter on
openness to new experiences

00:25:10.150 --> 00:25:13.060
and how it's going to be
really super important.

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:19.410
Building time to daydream
and reflect, like journal

00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:21.067
about your
experiences and really

00:25:21.067 --> 00:25:22.400
get a chance to understand that.

00:25:22.400 --> 00:25:24.110
What are some other things?

00:25:24.110 --> 00:25:26.590
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: I think one
of the most important things

00:25:26.590 --> 00:25:29.800
is openness to experience,
which we have a big chapter on.

00:25:29.800 --> 00:25:31.650
And this is actually
a personality trait

00:25:31.650 --> 00:25:34.210
that's the number one predictor
of creative achievement

00:25:34.210 --> 00:25:36.934
across all fields
in arts and science.

00:25:36.934 --> 00:25:38.850
And so this can take a
lot of different forms.

00:25:38.850 --> 00:25:43.050
But really, any sort of
new experiences or new ways

00:25:43.050 --> 00:25:44.790
of approaching things,
or even walking

00:25:44.790 --> 00:25:47.400
a different way to work--
that sounds so trivial,

00:25:47.400 --> 00:25:51.900
but just rewiring
your brain patterns

00:25:51.900 --> 00:25:53.820
and getting into
a different state

00:25:53.820 --> 00:25:56.350
actually makes a
very big difference,

00:25:56.350 --> 00:25:57.920
and it can sort of,
on subtle levels,

00:25:57.920 --> 00:25:59.910
and then eventually
on larger levels,

00:25:59.910 --> 00:26:03.080
change the way that you think
and give way to new ideas.

00:26:03.080 --> 00:26:05.730
So people who have
studied abroad,

00:26:05.730 --> 00:26:08.450
they've done studies and
found that they perform better

00:26:08.450 --> 00:26:11.540
on tests of creative thinking
after college students study

00:26:11.540 --> 00:26:12.040
abroad.

00:26:12.040 --> 00:26:15.787
And people who-- what are
some of the other ones?

00:26:15.787 --> 00:26:17.120
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Immigrants.

00:26:17.120 --> 00:26:18.078
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:26:18.078 --> 00:26:22.080
Immigrants tend to bring this
influx of art and culture

00:26:22.080 --> 00:26:24.960
into a new place, which
stimulates broader,

00:26:24.960 --> 00:26:31.400
societal-wide shifts in thinking
and in art and science and tech

00:26:31.400 --> 00:26:32.380
and that kind of thing.

00:26:32.380 --> 00:26:32.810
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Totally.

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:35.470
The big thing is to keep
cycling through your mindsets,

00:26:35.470 --> 00:26:36.460
your modes of thinking.

00:26:36.460 --> 00:26:37.960
Keep cycling all
throughout the day.

00:26:37.960 --> 00:26:39.810
Don't get stuck.

00:26:39.810 --> 00:26:42.110
If you're focusing on a
problem and you're like,

00:26:42.110 --> 00:26:43.490
OK, let's stay up all night.

00:26:43.490 --> 00:26:44.920
We're going to solve this,
and we're not leaving

00:26:44.920 --> 00:26:46.010
till we solve this problem.

00:26:46.010 --> 00:26:47.718
That's very unlikely
we're going to solve

00:26:47.718 --> 00:26:49.206
the problem that night.

00:26:49.206 --> 00:26:51.560
It's really important to
have that time to cycle

00:26:51.560 --> 00:26:53.180
through these different
mental states,

00:26:53.180 --> 00:26:57.255
because we know that's how
creativity works in the brain.

00:26:57.255 --> 00:26:58.130
SPEAKER 1: Thank you.

00:27:00.730 --> 00:27:03.250
AUDIENCE: OK, so it sounds like
diversity of new experiences

00:27:03.250 --> 00:27:06.200
is really important to
help train creativity.

00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:08.700
I think you mentioned journaling
a few different times-- one

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:12.090
as a way to deal with
trauma, and also as a way to,

00:27:12.090 --> 00:27:13.770
I think improve creativity.

00:27:13.770 --> 00:27:14.515
Did you say that?

00:27:14.515 --> 00:27:15.890
Could you elaborate
a little more

00:27:15.890 --> 00:27:17.817
on journaling and its effect?

00:27:17.817 --> 00:27:18.900
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Yeah.

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:21.880
What it requires is that
you're actively and cognitively

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:24.410
processing what has happened
to you throughout the day,

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:25.800
and that you're making meaning.

00:27:25.800 --> 00:27:29.610
You're trying to actually
tie it to your life--

00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:32.010
your past experiences,
your future experiences.

00:27:34.965 --> 00:27:36.340
Before you go to
bed every night,

00:27:36.340 --> 00:27:38.600
we know in positive
psychology it's

00:27:38.600 --> 00:27:40.510
good to write and reflect
on the things that

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:43.955
went wrong during the day and
then say, what was the point?

00:27:43.955 --> 00:27:45.080
What can I learn from that?

00:27:45.080 --> 00:27:47.160
Constantly be in
problem-based mode.

00:27:47.160 --> 00:27:49.130
And then also, write
three good things

00:27:49.130 --> 00:27:51.445
that you're happy about that
day before you go to bed.

00:27:51.445 --> 00:27:53.320
So it's called the three
good things exercise

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.890
that I teach my students in
my positive psychology class.

00:27:55.890 --> 00:27:57.810
And that makes it
much more likely

00:27:57.810 --> 00:28:03.980
that you will wake up the next
day feeling more ready and able

00:28:03.980 --> 00:28:05.290
to tackle the day.

00:28:05.290 --> 00:28:07.564
And you could see how
that positive emotions--

00:28:07.564 --> 00:28:09.230
we know positive
emotions are correlated

00:28:09.230 --> 00:28:12.780
with creativity and probability
for creative thinking,

00:28:12.780 --> 00:28:14.840
and insightful thinking.

00:28:14.840 --> 00:28:16.930
So to the extent to
which you put that

00:28:16.930 --> 00:28:19.789
into your journals, that allows
you to have fresh outlooks

00:28:19.789 --> 00:28:21.830
and perspectives on life
that's going to increase

00:28:21.830 --> 00:28:24.430
your creativity, I would think.

00:28:24.430 --> 00:28:27.670
If you want specific exercises,
you can email me, though.

00:28:27.670 --> 00:28:29.300
There's some great
stuff by Pennebaker

00:28:29.300 --> 00:28:32.167
and others that can get
you started right away.

00:28:32.167 --> 00:28:33.250
AUDIENCE: Cool, thank you.

00:28:36.571 --> 00:28:38.820
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: By the
way, I went to high school

00:28:38.820 --> 00:28:41.480
with these three.

00:28:41.480 --> 00:28:45.394
And it's so surreal that
they're sitting there right now.

00:28:45.394 --> 00:28:46.560
They're really good friends.

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:47.393
AUDIENCE: Hi, Scott.

00:28:47.393 --> 00:28:48.510
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Hey.

00:28:48.510 --> 00:28:51.940
AUDIENCE: What would you say
makes society value or not

00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:53.420
value creativity?

00:28:53.420 --> 00:28:56.016
Why are there are so
many starving artists?

00:28:56.016 --> 00:28:57.890
Why do you hear about
the painter who becomes

00:28:57.890 --> 00:29:00.160
famous only after his death?

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:03.350
Why do we want to consume so
much content, but maybe not pay

00:29:03.350 --> 00:29:04.650
for it?

00:29:04.650 --> 00:29:09.522
What are some of your
psychology thoughts on that?

00:29:09.522 --> 00:29:11.480
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: I
think I'm talking a lot.

00:29:11.480 --> 00:29:12.950
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah, I'll
just jump in really quick.

00:29:12.950 --> 00:29:13.770
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: I
feel like I'm yakking.

00:29:13.770 --> 00:29:15.145
CAROLYN GREGOIRE:
I think we sort

00:29:15.145 --> 00:29:17.570
of value creativity in theory.

00:29:17.570 --> 00:29:20.480
We celebrate, obviously,
great musicians

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:24.080
and artists and innovators,
and kind of hold them up

00:29:24.080 --> 00:29:25.450
and put them on pedestals.

00:29:25.450 --> 00:29:28.910
But we tend to not look at
what it took to actually get

00:29:28.910 --> 00:29:32.480
there, and the sort of
challenges that are inherent,

00:29:32.480 --> 00:29:34.770
and the failures
that are inherent

00:29:34.770 --> 00:29:36.580
to the creative process.

00:29:36.580 --> 00:29:39.760
And especially, you see
this in schools for sure,

00:29:39.760 --> 00:29:41.730
and also in a lot
of organizations.

00:29:41.730 --> 00:29:44.780
I expect that Google is a little
more progressive on this front.

00:29:44.780 --> 00:29:48.600
But most organizations say
that they desire innovation,

00:29:48.600 --> 00:29:50.777
and that they want
creative new products.

00:29:50.777 --> 00:29:51.860
They want creative people.

00:29:51.860 --> 00:29:53.318
They want to do
things differently.

00:29:53.318 --> 00:29:59.470
But they're actually
completely unwilling to make

00:29:59.470 --> 00:30:01.210
the sacrifices
that that requires.

00:30:01.210 --> 00:30:04.802
So that's allowing people to
maybe have more freedom, or--

00:30:04.802 --> 00:30:06.510
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
Pretty much choosing

00:30:06.510 --> 00:30:07.920
what project you
want to work on.

00:30:07.920 --> 00:30:10.740
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah,
allowing people to sort of think

00:30:10.740 --> 00:30:13.330
about things in a new way, or
kind of write their own rules

00:30:13.330 --> 00:30:16.660
in some sense, or
just accepting failure

00:30:16.660 --> 00:30:19.240
as a path to doing something
really differently.

00:30:19.240 --> 00:30:21.430
So really, I think
in the workplaces

00:30:21.430 --> 00:30:23.930
and in schools is where
we see that the most.

00:30:23.930 --> 00:30:25.013
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Yeah.

00:30:25.013 --> 00:30:26.414
And in schools, for sure.

00:30:26.414 --> 00:30:27.830
I mean, we have
this whole culture

00:30:27.830 --> 00:30:29.370
of standardized testing.

00:30:29.370 --> 00:30:30.580
So we teach to the test.

00:30:30.580 --> 00:30:33.270
So we don't have a
revision process.

00:30:33.270 --> 00:30:36.110
There's something like, you
got a D. You're like, OK,

00:30:36.110 --> 00:30:36.750
I'm screwed.

00:30:36.750 --> 00:30:41.290
I got a D. As opposed to,
look, you didn't fail.

00:30:41.290 --> 00:30:44.030
You've got a D. So there's still
stuff we can work out here.

00:30:44.030 --> 00:30:46.800
They don't frame it
that way in school.

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:49.000
There's so many ways
we could be framing

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:52.042
things that make
school like, oh, this

00:30:52.042 --> 00:30:53.250
is all about personal growth.

00:30:53.250 --> 00:30:55.900
This is all about--
our book is very much

00:30:55.900 --> 00:30:58.700
a personal-growth-oriented
book, I will say.

00:30:58.700 --> 00:31:00.410
Do you agree?

00:31:00.410 --> 00:31:03.960
This book is not about-- I
have most respect recorded

00:31:03.960 --> 00:31:06.390
and everything for my
colleague Angela Duckworth

00:31:06.390 --> 00:31:09.700
and the work on grit and all
that-- very important work.

00:31:09.700 --> 00:31:13.100
But we also think that
sometimes, the process itself,

00:31:13.100 --> 00:31:16.100
without the goal-oriented
aspect of it,

00:31:16.100 --> 00:31:19.900
can be even more
conducive to creativity

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:22.682
than being specifically
goal-oriented.

00:31:22.682 --> 00:31:23.640
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Yeah.

00:31:23.640 --> 00:31:25.500
I think also, our
obsession with efficiency

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:29.170
is kind of at odds with
creative work, which

00:31:29.170 --> 00:31:32.440
is a bit more meandering
and doesn't always

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.690
have a clear outcome.

00:31:34.690 --> 00:31:36.050
And this starts so early now.

00:31:36.050 --> 00:31:39.120
I think even preschool kids
have so little free time,

00:31:39.120 --> 00:31:42.970
like 30% less than
they did in the '70s.

00:31:42.970 --> 00:31:47.000
So that's just not really-- if
we want people to sort of let

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.990
their minds go and
come up with new things

00:31:48.990 --> 00:31:52.510
and change the
paradigm, it's not

00:31:52.510 --> 00:31:56.090
going to come from squeezing
activities into slots,

00:31:56.090 --> 00:31:59.990
and not trying to write a
book in a really short period

00:31:59.990 --> 00:32:02.600
or come up with a new product
in a ridiculously short period,

00:32:02.600 --> 00:32:03.960
because you're just
going and going

00:32:03.960 --> 00:32:05.251
and moving onto the next thing.

00:32:05.251 --> 00:32:07.460
That's just not really--
creativity works

00:32:07.460 --> 00:32:09.369
in a completely different way.

00:32:09.369 --> 00:32:11.910
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: I mean, I
hope this stuff doesn't-- some

00:32:11.910 --> 00:32:15.320
of it may sound really corny,
or really like soft, right?

00:32:15.320 --> 00:32:18.880
If I said to you, you really
should make in your day

00:32:18.880 --> 00:32:21.960
a play break where you
literally-- there's

00:32:21.960 --> 00:32:24.660
45 minutes you could
call anyone at work

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:27.620
and be like, let's play Frisbee.

00:32:27.620 --> 00:32:28.870
You think that's corny, right?

00:32:28.870 --> 00:32:30.350
You'd be like, ugh.

00:32:30.350 --> 00:32:33.440
But there is research showing
that actually, the more that

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:36.467
you build a play
mindset into work,

00:32:36.467 --> 00:32:39.050
the more that you come back and
you're more likely to actually

00:32:39.050 --> 00:32:40.430
solve the problem.

00:32:40.430 --> 00:32:44.060
So I think it's stuff that
really matters, even though we

00:32:44.060 --> 00:32:45.090
kind of look down on it.

00:32:48.360 --> 00:32:49.809
Yeah.

00:32:49.809 --> 00:32:51.600
AUDIENCE: So I noticed
most of the research

00:32:51.600 --> 00:32:54.660
seems to be done on
artists, musicians,

00:32:54.660 --> 00:32:57.570
the fields we traditionally
think of as creative.

00:32:57.570 --> 00:33:00.820
Is it because it's easy
to study those sorts of--

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:03.660
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
They want to studied.

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:05.404
Artists love it.

00:33:05.404 --> 00:33:06.570
AUDIENCE: So I'm wondering--

00:33:06.570 --> 00:33:09.258
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Tell
me more about myself.

00:33:09.258 --> 00:33:10.660
Sorry.

00:33:10.660 --> 00:33:13.440
AUDIENCE: Is the research
done on those manifestations

00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:15.320
of creativity applicable
to maybe the sorts

00:33:15.320 --> 00:33:16.920
that we're interested
here in terms

00:33:16.920 --> 00:33:20.750
of solving technical
or scientific problems?

00:33:20.750 --> 00:33:22.690
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
Totally fair question.

00:33:22.690 --> 00:33:23.290
I think so.

00:33:23.290 --> 00:33:26.654
I mean, I've looked at
research on the sciences.

00:33:26.654 --> 00:33:28.070
So we don't just
look at the arts,

00:33:28.070 --> 00:33:29.903
but I've also done
research in the sciences.

00:33:29.903 --> 00:33:32.790
And we find that
intellectual curiosity

00:33:32.790 --> 00:33:34.970
is a very strong predictor
of creative achievement

00:33:34.970 --> 00:33:37.570
in the sciences, much
more than in the arts.

00:33:37.570 --> 00:33:39.960
The arts, openness to
experience was more important.

00:33:39.960 --> 00:33:42.990
But we find that more
high-level abstract sort

00:33:42.990 --> 00:33:45.390
of level of reasoning, level
of intellectual curiosity--

00:33:45.390 --> 00:33:47.750
like coming up with lots
of different possibilities

00:33:47.750 --> 00:33:50.810
and really being open
in an intellectual way--

00:33:50.810 --> 00:33:53.760
is a much better predictor
of scientific achievement.

00:33:53.760 --> 00:33:56.970
So we found that.

00:33:56.970 --> 00:33:59.810
I don't know if there's any
real in-depth longitudinal

00:33:59.810 --> 00:34:03.070
study of computer scientists.

00:34:03.070 --> 00:34:05.520
To me, I don't know if
such a study has been done.

00:34:05.520 --> 00:34:09.330
Although I lived with a computer
scientist for a couple years,

00:34:09.330 --> 00:34:11.080
and I have some case studies.

00:34:11.080 --> 00:34:12.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:12.860 --> 00:34:16.199
I don't know if any real-- yeah?

00:34:16.199 --> 00:34:18.670
AUDIENCE: I was curious, have
you encountered any research

00:34:18.670 --> 00:34:22.330
on people using
lucid dreaming to tap

00:34:22.330 --> 00:34:23.844
into their creative sources?

00:34:23.844 --> 00:34:24.639
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
Oh, the next question's

00:34:24.639 --> 00:34:25.805
going to be drugs, isn't it?

00:34:25.805 --> 00:34:27.040
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:27.040 --> 00:34:29.920
The gateway question is
always the lucid dreaming.

00:34:29.920 --> 00:34:33.250
The next one is always LSD.

00:34:33.250 --> 00:34:36.300
Admit it, someone
had that waiting.

00:34:36.300 --> 00:34:38.469
Lucid dreaming is a
fascinating phenomenon.

00:34:38.469 --> 00:34:41.350
And it is possible
to train yourself.

00:34:41.350 --> 00:34:43.610
It's not guaranteed
if you train yourself.

00:34:43.610 --> 00:34:47.029
But the normal
areas of the brain--

00:34:47.029 --> 00:34:49.570
remember I was talking about
the executive attention network?

00:34:49.570 --> 00:34:53.560
Well, that's normally
silence when we're dreaming.

00:34:53.560 --> 00:34:57.690
And that's why our dreams tend
to be so bizarre, because there

00:34:57.690 --> 00:35:02.530
is no higher order of control
that is making it organized.

00:35:02.530 --> 00:35:04.450
So it's sort of like
every person for themself

00:35:04.450 --> 00:35:06.830
in your dreams-- like anything
goes, and then you wake up

00:35:06.830 --> 00:35:08.913
and you're horrified that
you just had that dream.

00:35:08.913 --> 00:35:11.830
You're like, I'm not telling
anyone about that one.

00:35:11.830 --> 00:35:14.570
But you can actually
train in a lucid way

00:35:14.570 --> 00:35:16.400
to activate your
executive attention

00:35:16.400 --> 00:35:18.150
network during dreaming.

00:35:18.150 --> 00:35:20.590
And it's really
surreal when you do

00:35:20.590 --> 00:35:24.330
that, like literally
surreal because you're like,

00:35:24.330 --> 00:35:29.370
I'm able to take an active role
in organizing the structure

00:35:29.370 --> 00:35:31.165
of this dream right now.

00:35:31.165 --> 00:35:31.970
You know what?

00:35:31.970 --> 00:35:35.540
I'm going to walk through that
door right now in the dream.

00:35:35.540 --> 00:35:37.130
And people can be
trained to do that.

00:35:37.130 --> 00:35:38.060
It's fascinating.

00:35:38.060 --> 00:35:39.580
Now, you didn't
ask this question,

00:35:39.580 --> 00:35:41.205
but I am curious--
the extent to which,

00:35:41.205 --> 00:35:42.720
are lucid dreamers
more creative?

00:35:42.720 --> 00:35:44.350
And that's an
interesting question,

00:35:44.350 --> 00:35:46.641
and I don't think any study
has ever been done on that.

00:35:46.641 --> 00:35:50.470
But there is some emerging
research on LSD and creativity,

00:35:50.470 --> 00:35:54.320
if anyone's interested in that--
which Carolyn can talk about.

00:35:54.320 --> 00:35:56.570
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Well, I
was actually just going to--

00:35:56.570 --> 00:35:57.100
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Did
he have another question?

00:35:57.100 --> 00:35:57.945
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: Oh, sorry.

00:35:57.945 --> 00:35:58.510
Go ahead.

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:00.590
Well, another thing
sleep-related-- or

00:36:00.590 --> 00:36:04.630
dreaming-related,
rather-- is hypnagogia

00:36:04.630 --> 00:36:06.700
is this state between
sleep and wakefulness.

00:36:06.700 --> 00:36:09.200
I don't know if you ever-- this
sometimes happens to me when

00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:10.700
I'm meditating,
which probably means

00:36:10.700 --> 00:36:14.010
I'm not a very good meditator--
when you are sort of almost

00:36:14.010 --> 00:36:16.210
asleep, and your brain
is just in that place

00:36:16.210 --> 00:36:18.620
where it's spitting nonsense?

00:36:18.620 --> 00:36:21.490
That is actually a really
creatively fertile time,

00:36:21.490 --> 00:36:23.450
because your brain
is going into REM,

00:36:23.450 --> 00:36:26.080
but it's also cycling
through things

00:36:26.080 --> 00:36:29.029
that have happened in the day,
like memories and ideas and all

00:36:29.029 --> 00:36:29.570
these things.

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:31.630
So have the benefits
of sleep in terms

00:36:31.630 --> 00:36:35.890
of loosening cognitive control,
but then also your mind

00:36:35.890 --> 00:36:38.050
is still active.

00:36:38.050 --> 00:36:40.400
So a lot of people have
tried to harness this.

00:36:40.400 --> 00:36:42.730
I think Dali did some
sort of weird experiment

00:36:42.730 --> 00:36:45.591
where he took a nap and
had something roll down

00:36:45.591 --> 00:36:48.090
his hand slowly, and then when
it felt like he would wake up

00:36:48.090 --> 00:36:49.506
so he caught himself
in that state

00:36:49.506 --> 00:36:51.232
before he actually fell asleep.

00:36:51.232 --> 00:36:53.690
So that's kind of an interesting
thing to pay attention to.

00:36:53.690 --> 00:36:56.840
It can be difficult to remember
the insights of that time,

00:36:56.840 --> 00:37:00.470
but it's like your
brain is loosening

00:37:00.470 --> 00:37:04.400
the control and the filter,
and more and more is coming in.

00:37:04.400 --> 00:37:07.937
So it's worth paying attention
to and exploring a little bit.

00:37:07.937 --> 00:37:09.020
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: Yeah.

00:37:09.020 --> 00:37:12.100
Also, two glasses of wine
improves your creativity,

00:37:12.100 --> 00:37:13.280
as well.

00:37:13.280 --> 00:37:15.800
It is good to reduce the
executive functions a little

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:17.280
bit, but not completely.

00:37:21.230 --> 00:37:23.280
AUDIENCE: So besides
drugs and meditation,

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:25.150
what can you do
to train yourself

00:37:25.150 --> 00:37:27.215
to lose control and
become more creative?

00:37:27.215 --> 00:37:28.840
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: There
are cutesy little exercises--

00:37:28.840 --> 00:37:29.870
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: That's
a really good question.

00:37:29.870 --> 00:37:30.930
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN: --that
scientists are working on.

00:37:30.930 --> 00:37:33.150
Yeah, it is a great question.

00:37:33.150 --> 00:37:37.500
The science of creativity
in terms of developing it

00:37:37.500 --> 00:37:40.501
is an underdeveloped field.

00:37:40.501 --> 00:37:42.250
At the Imagination
Institute where I work,

00:37:42.250 --> 00:37:45.070
we've just done a $3
million grant competition

00:37:45.070 --> 00:37:46.940
where we had people
from all over the world

00:37:46.940 --> 00:37:48.710
try to provide us
with their ideas

00:37:48.710 --> 00:37:50.690
on how we can
improve imagination

00:37:50.690 --> 00:37:52.720
and measure it as well.

00:37:52.720 --> 00:37:54.477
And the results
of those projects,

00:37:54.477 --> 00:37:56.310
which are listed on the
Imagination website,

00:37:56.310 --> 00:37:58.150
will be out next year.

00:37:58.150 --> 00:38:00.360
And we hope-- we've
given them money.

00:38:00.360 --> 00:38:02.020
I hope they did
something interesting.

00:38:02.020 --> 00:38:04.190
And so we'll see next
year what they found.

00:38:04.190 --> 00:38:06.170
But there are some
cutesy exercises.

00:38:06.170 --> 00:38:08.170
There are some exercises
where people-- have you

00:38:08.170 --> 00:38:11.720
guys heard of de Bono and stuff,
like lateral thinking exercises

00:38:11.720 --> 00:38:12.222
and things?

00:38:12.222 --> 00:38:14.430
There are exercises you can
do where you can actively

00:38:14.430 --> 00:38:18.320
put through a random
word generator

00:38:18.320 --> 00:38:20.417
various words, things
that you're working on,

00:38:20.417 --> 00:38:21.500
your project's working on.

00:38:21.500 --> 00:38:23.620
And then you've got
to, as an exercise,

00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:26.090
think of how are these
three related to each other,

00:38:26.090 --> 00:38:28.200
and think creatively about that.

00:38:28.200 --> 00:38:30.600
The point is that you want
to get your creative juices

00:38:30.600 --> 00:38:31.540
stimulated.

00:38:31.540 --> 00:38:32.850
That didn't sound good.

00:38:32.850 --> 00:38:36.700
But you really want to get
in that-- so much of it

00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:37.880
is a mindset.

00:38:37.880 --> 00:38:40.150
And you find that
creativity really does get

00:38:40.150 --> 00:38:42.870
blocked when you get
too serious, too down

00:38:42.870 --> 00:38:45.400
one garden path.

00:38:45.400 --> 00:38:49.690
Creativity is like a spreading
activation model in the brain.

00:38:49.690 --> 00:38:52.180
You're going to be most
likely do to access the most

00:38:52.180 --> 00:38:53.640
remote associations.

00:38:53.640 --> 00:38:58.260
So there are exercises you
can do to kind of on-the-spot,

00:38:58.260 --> 00:39:00.940
if you feel like you're
getting too down a single path

00:39:00.940 --> 00:39:02.030
to stimulate it.

00:39:02.030 --> 00:39:06.452
But I hope we can come up
with better things than that.

00:39:06.452 --> 00:39:09.612
CAROLYN GREGOIRE: I don't know,
maybe hypnosis or something--

00:39:09.612 --> 00:39:11.820
if you're looking specifically
that sort of loosening

00:39:11.820 --> 00:39:14.030
that occurs with
psychedelics and dreaming

00:39:14.030 --> 00:39:17.320
and that kind of thing,
I can think of maybe

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:18.540
hypnosis and breath work.

00:39:18.540 --> 00:39:21.770
But I'm not necessarily
suggesting those things.

00:39:21.770 --> 00:39:24.630
But it's an interesting
question, yeah.

00:39:24.630 --> 00:39:25.880
SPEAKER 1: Well, thank you.

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:28.980
There was one question
that I did have.

00:39:28.980 --> 00:39:32.590
So it was once believed that
creativity was restricted

00:39:32.590 --> 00:39:34.670
to the right side of the brain.

00:39:34.670 --> 00:39:37.130
But the understandings
have changed now.

00:39:37.130 --> 00:39:40.810
What else has changed recently,
like after the book was

00:39:40.810 --> 00:39:43.300
published or just that
you would want to mention?

00:39:43.300 --> 00:39:44.300
CAROLYN GREGOIRE:
That's a good question.

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:44.780
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
Well really,

00:39:44.780 --> 00:39:47.030
what we were talking about,
these large-scale brain

00:39:47.030 --> 00:39:48.738
networks is a much
better way of thinking

00:39:48.738 --> 00:39:51.700
about how creativity happens
than left-brain, right-brain.

00:39:51.700 --> 00:39:54.980
There are some interesting
lateral specialization effects.

00:39:54.980 --> 00:39:57.790
So we do know that the
right side of the brain does

00:39:57.790 --> 00:40:01.960
tend to process more non-verbal,
artistic, and the left brain

00:40:01.960 --> 00:40:03.300
kind of more language.

00:40:03.300 --> 00:40:05.800
But with that said, the
whole creative process

00:40:05.800 --> 00:40:07.824
seems to draw on these
large-scale brain

00:40:07.824 --> 00:40:09.990
networks that operate in
the left and the right side

00:40:09.990 --> 00:40:11.460
of the brain.

00:40:11.460 --> 00:40:13.670
And so it requires kind
of a whole-brain approach.

00:40:13.670 --> 00:40:17.050
I mean, if I could show you
a picture of what creativity

00:40:17.050 --> 00:40:20.370
looks like in the brain,
throughout the whole process

00:40:20.370 --> 00:40:24.132
it's pretty much every part
is activated at some point.

00:40:24.132 --> 00:40:26.590
And that's a nice way to tie
together the whole messy minds

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:27.240
thing, as well.

00:40:27.240 --> 00:40:29.340
Just like I said,
your personality--

00:40:29.340 --> 00:40:31.880
throughout the
course of your day,

00:40:31.880 --> 00:40:35.600
no matter even if you say, I'm
an introvert, or I'm agreeable,

00:40:35.600 --> 00:40:36.820
I'm not agreeable.

00:40:36.820 --> 00:40:38.292
Even if you think
you're a saint,

00:40:38.292 --> 00:40:40.500
even saints, if you follow
them throughout the course

00:40:40.500 --> 00:40:43.120
of the day, are jerks sometimes.

00:40:43.120 --> 00:40:46.340
So it's constantly cycling all
throughout the thing, and kind

00:40:46.340 --> 00:40:49.850
of being open and embracing that
messiness of human personality

00:40:49.850 --> 00:40:51.477
structure.

00:40:51.477 --> 00:40:52.060
SPEAKER 1: OK.

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:53.650
Thank you so much for coming.

00:40:53.650 --> 00:40:55.650
It was great talking to you.

00:40:55.650 --> 00:40:57.170
It was very helpful.

00:40:57.170 --> 00:40:59.420
Thanks a lot, and thank
you, everyone for coming.

00:40:59.420 --> 00:40:59.960
SCOTT BARRY KAUFMAN:
Thanks for inviting us.

00:40:59.960 --> 00:41:01.920
SPEAKER 1: There's
books in the back.

